    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-08-11T05:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-08-11T05:00:00-05:00" n="862"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d862">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">124.613/1171: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Steinhardt</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-08-11T13:00:00+03:00"
                            >August 11, 1941—1 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received August 12—9:30 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1470. Victor V. Shiffer, a Soviet member of the Embassy staff now stationed at
                    Kazan left his quarters early on the evening of August 7 for a walk and did not
                    return. Dickerson subsequently ascertained from the local authorities that
                    Shiffer had been detained and sent to Moscow by the “decision” of the Central
                    authorities without the knowledge of the local government.<note n="47"
                        xml:id="d862fn47">For correspondence concerning earlier arrests of Soviet
                        employees of the American Embassy in Moscow, see <ref
                            target="frus1933-39#pg_319">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, The Soviet Union, 1933–1939,
                            pp. 319</ref>–<ref target="frus1933-39#pg_320">320</ref>, <ref
                            target="frus1933-39#pg_375">375</ref>, <ref target="frus1933-39#pg_392"
                            >392</ref>, <ref target="frus1933-39#pg_400">400</ref>, <ref
                            target="frus1933-39#pg_494">494</ref>, <ref target="frus1933-39#pg_631"
                            >631</ref>, and <ref target="frus1933-39#pg_635">635</ref>–<ref
                            target="frus1933-39#pg_638">638</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <p>I have addressed a note to the People’s Commissariat for Foreign Affairs
                    reporting this occurrence, requesting that an inquiry be made, and that I be
                    advised the outcome.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Steinhardt</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
